18 appropriation in the amount of $2 billion into such fund, which shall be appropriated from
19 the Revenue Shortfall Reserve. The General Assembly shall be authorized, but not
20 required, to appropriate additional amounts into such fund. All moneys appropriated into
21 the Children First Trust Fund shall not be subject to the provisions of Article III, Section
22 IX, Paragraph IV(c), relating to the lapsing of funds, and shall be used to provide
23 scholarships, grants, or other forms of financial assistance for child care services in this
24 state; provided, however, that a portion of the moneys appropriated to the Children First
25 Trust Fund shall be invested and reinvested in a manner as provided by law. Moneys
26 received from returns on such investments and reinvestments shall be deposited into the
27 Children First Trust Fund and shall be used to provide scholarships, grants, or other forms
28 of financial assistance for child care services in this state. The General Assembly shall be
29 authorized to provide by law for any matters relating to the purpose or provisions of this
30 subparagraph."
31 SECTION 2.
32 The above proposed amendment to the Constitution shall be published and submitted as
33 provided in Article X, Section I, Paragraph II of the Constitution. The ballot submitting the
34 above proposed amendment shall have written or printed thereon the following:
35 "( ) YES Shall the Constitution of Georgia be amended so as to authorize the General
36 ( ) NO Assembly to use a portion of the state's historic, multi-year revenue surplus
37 to create a self-sustaining Children First Trust Fund for the purpose of
38 providing access to child care services in this state?"
39 All persons desiring to vote in favor of ratifying the proposed amendment shall vote "Yes."
40 All persons desiring to vote against ratifying the proposed amendment shall vote "No." If
41 such amendment shall be ratified as provided in said Paragraph of the Constitution, it shall
42 become a part of the Constitution of this state.
